Samuel N? F. Bangor, Oct 13 1836
Bangor Oct 13th 1856
Dear Mother
I suppose you like to hear often from us if we have nothing to say. We are I think, all well, most certainly I am, Irving cries most of the time when awake I think his teeth trouble him some and he very much need a little "wholesome neglect" pity he cant have it. Have not heard from I soul Issac?since you left. The Roman Catholic Cathedral was consecrated yesterday a great day for the Irish. Mr. Jebbels? commenced to finish off two chambers today, he hopes to get them plastered this week. he does them by the job. does the work and furnishes all material for $52.45. with what a different feeling I take hold to do any thing about the house now from what I have ever done before. I do it now because I know it ought to be done. it gives me no pleasure, my heart
Completed

is not in it as it was and should be in every thing which goes to make home pleasant and convenient. I know that instead of mourning over my present lot I ought, to give thanks for the many happy days which have been mine, the memory of which will ever be blessed Oh that my tongue on my pen might be unloosed that I might make known all that is burning within me. it seems to me that I have been denied the power of telling all that I would more than most are able to do, and I suppose I must learn more to show by deeds and actions what I would wish to express so I will make no further effort to express thoughts or feelings to night I have taken the place of a boarder this week. my feelings are at times almost beyond control, but a sense of duty has so far sustained me and I trust that will continue to.
To Percie?. Father wants to see you very much. and he wants you to be a very good boy. always mind what what Grandmother
Completed

or Uncle Charles or Aunt Albina tell you always mind very quick, and always be very kind to Mary when you play with her and perhaps one of these days father will come up to Milo and bring you and Grandmother home with him because father wishes very much to have you and Grandmother here with him, and want you to be glad when father comes after you, and father will be glad if Grandmother tells me that my little Percie has been a good boy and now my boy good night may God watch over you while you are asleep and protect you, and you will learn to love God who is so good to you.
L.W. Furber
Completed

Elria? April 13th 1857
Dear Mother
I suppose you would like to see my hand writing by the time this will reach you. you will see by what I've wrote Eliah about how I am getting along, I read a letter unclear by Anna from you the day I reached here. you of course must be a practical judge of some things or persons upon which you give an opinion, if you knew all that I know I dont see how you could write as you do, it is a great comfort to me to know that you love and esteem me. I only wish that I could more than I do merit that esteem and love, if I could find words how gladly would I express to you the deep love and gratitude which I bear to you. May heaven bless you. How much I want to see Percie. yet I feel that it is best that he is with you. tell that father sends him a great deal of love and wants him to be a good boy. and I will write him a letter when I get to Minnesota. I have been spending the time here very pleasantly between the
Completed

Two houses. I stay nights at Anna's we read some. talk some, try to sing at times but often have to stop and cry, I hope to hear from you often With much love to all, yours affectionately S.W. Furber
S.W. Furber
Elysia? April 13th '57 Bangor
Fam.? Elysia? April 13 /57
Completed

S.W. Furber Elysia April 20 '57 Bangor
Elysia April 20th 1857
Dear Mother
Tis a beautiful morning, how fresh and invigorating, I returned here from Brookville Saturday evening, I had a very pleasant trip then. although the road beyond Kittanning was abundantly bad. 44 miles by mud cart, time seventeen hours fro 10 AM to 3 AM the road in places on the Crows of Mills. with the outer wheels within eighteen inches of the edge of precipices seven hundred feet in heighth and no protection to keep the carriage in the road. riding in such places in a dark night with out any light and the driver filled with bad whiskey is not very conducive to sleep. How ever I've been and returned all safe, There is much in travelling through such a country to awaken thought and deep feeling and high asperations. I should think that the poetry and the music of one living in such a place must possess
Completed

an elevation of thought and character beyond the reach of one whose life is confined to narrower spheres of polished halls
I was very much interested yesterday in two meetings held here by Mr Ian Metre? of the five points Mission school, who is looking up homes for children he had three little boys here, he gave an account of their operations, and presented the claims of these destitute children in a simple, clean and most affecting manner. the sympathies of all were arroused and few could listin to him with dry eyes. I think it is good to have our sympathies thus wrought upon, so that we may be led to say
"O give me tears for others woe And patience for my own"
The weather here is very cold it has snowed almost every day for a week past untill to day I do not think it is any mroe
Completed

forward here than in Bangor. the grass is beginning to look green, but no leaves to be seen. Ice is yet in Lake Pepin I shall leave here Wednesday, stop one day in Chicago and over the sabbath with a cousin in Northern Ill. (Nancy Wingate) and probably get to St Paul about the last day of this month. I have been very well since I left, am now wanting very much to hear from you and Percie and all the others at Bangor, please write often and let me know all about Percie. Every thing in relation to him will possess a great interist to me it seems to me that no one else can know how I wish to know every thing which relates to him to know and to feel that he will have the best care taken of him and be subject to the best possible influences, will not lessen my desire to know all about him, and for this I must depend almost entirely upon
Completed

you, and I know that you will find much satisfaction in giving me this information
Enclosed I send you a copy of a peice from the flora?, it seems to be very beautiful and truthful.
To me, the thought, that our dear Frey? has given a direction to Percie's character and impulses which will ever go with him to the end of life is very dear, I may say almost sacred I trust I might improve every present opportunity for doing good, and not throw upon the future what belongs to the present, not knowing that there will be for me, in time, any other than the present, Ask Percie when he says his prayers at night if he will not ask God to bless father, tell him that father asks God to take care of him every day. Much love to all
S.W. Furber
Completed

April 21st. Not having sent my letter last evening I open it this morning to add to it. This village was thrown into a state of much excitement yesterday by an incident upon the Pearl Road. The train due here from Cleveland about five P.M. ran over a cow at the East End of the East Bridge mutually knocking each other from the track. The Engine left the track as it went upon the bridge (the track is upon the top of the Bridge as at Kendalls Mills) the bridge is forty feet above the water and about 150 ft in length, there were two baggage cars one 2nd Class and the other 1st Class Cars, the Engine went over the bridge off the track and leaped from the abutment down the bank as it left the bridge the tender following it, the baggage cars went past the Engine and then down the bank, the near end of the second one stopping near the top of the bank the forward end of the 2nd Class
Completed

car resting upon it and the near end upon the road, the three first class cars stoping on there bridge with track torn all up under the forward one.
Two Engine men and a fireman on the Engine and tender and one or two were in the baggage cars
Not one person has been seriously injured, To stand and look upon the bridge with the torn track and broken floor upon the Engine and cars as they were last evening and know that no life was lost, no one dangerously injured, seems almost miraculous. It certainly calls for devout gratitude to God. 
How different might have been the scene. This morning the road is cleared, the track relaid and trains have passed over the bridge, which seems about as strange as the events of yesterday
Good bye
SWF
Completed

St Paul May 15th 1857
Dear Mother
Your letter of April 27 I see today on my return from Cottage Grove. I arrived here the first day of the month at 6:30 A.M. I left Elyria on Wednesday April 25th one day to Chicago. Stopped their one day. Spent a night with Alan & Anne? Cha's Thaxterwho were quite glad to see me, and I was glad to see Lizzie. I think that she is not very happy, and no one to blame but herself. She believes it is quite an act to learn to be content. Chicago I dislike very much. Flat and wet, I stopped a few days with Fred Wingate in DuPage County 20 miles West from Chicago, a very fine country.  The prairie is much more rolling than I had thought, ? proved land is worth $25 to 30 per acre wood enough if evenly distributed good water by digging 20 feet. Some of the country between them and Dunleith is flat and undesirable. I arrived at Dunleith Monday eve April 27
Completed

went directly aboard of a steamer for St. Paul. Fare $7.00 arrived at Lake Pepin Wednesday Eve April 29. Ice not out of the lake.Some 20 Boats waiting. Our boat the WS Nelson went into the ice and worked all night. Breaking ice to the great discomfort of nervous passengers. I enjoyed in much. Something to break the monotony of Steamboat life. Thursday morning we were joined by other Boats got through the lake at night and arrived at St. Paul at 6:30 A.M May 1st. I had a cold through all my journey and the day we got to Lake Pepin I was almost sick. laid in my berth all day , but watching the breaking of ice that night got me well, and have felt nicely all the time since. The scenery on the river is intensely beautiful and grand, evidently the design of a great architect.
I find my folks here all but Theodore for whom I have many fears. I went to Cottage Grove May 2 and came back here yesterday. You can probably judge better
Completed

than I can tell how I spent my time. 
Sometimes, often, we anticipate in the meeting of long absent ones more than we seem to realize, but with you I can say in all truth that I have enjoyed their day with great satisfaction, and not the least of my enjoyment have I found in the children. They so much love which we feel to be pure, I had not thought of it. I presume you wish to know how I like Minnesota, I like it well. The farming country about Cottage Grove is certainly very fine, there are some objections. Great cries, a scarcity of wood and water, as to wood the objection is not great, as a plenty of it can be got by drawing a miles. There are many little ponds which afford a great supply of water. But locally cannot be got less than from 100 to any unknown number of feet. They use storm and cement cisterns to get water for drinking. The land is excellent fully meeting my expectations.
I have not yet decided on anything for permanent business. Father will start East about the middle of June. do not
Completed

know how long he may stay. Oliver and Mr. Haskell were intending to go East in the fall. I shall make arrangements with some of them to accompany to Elyria, if you have no other opportunity. The Legislature has now been in session three weeks trying to dispose of the lands granted by Congress to this Terr(itory) for building ?roads they have made but little progress.
I hope to get a horse for I have heard? some of these projected mail roads.
I know you will write my often.
Tell Percie that father wants very much to see him and hopes he will be a good boy.
Much love to all.
S.W. Furber
St. Paul May 15th '57
Completed

S.W. Furber
St. Paul May 1857
May 25th 1857
Dear Mother:
It has been a rainy day. It is a rainy evening. Father is gone out as usual and I am almost lonesome. I did not know but you would like to see a plan of my present home and I have drawn a rough sketch. The rooms No from 1 to 5 are rented $180 Oper year. The others Father occupies, I do not think it a very convenient house. There is no chamber in the house, no clothes press, no place to store away anything. I shall have to send most of my things to Cottage Grove when they come. I can put one Buscara? and ? in every room and crowed in the old Secretary too, perhaps a ?. I have been back from the Grove 10 day. Have been out of town 3 days looking about. Should have
Completed

been away today if it had not rained. I expect to go in a few days to Crow Wing 120 miles up the river. I have the offer of one third of a town of 320 acres laid out for a village consisting of 1407 lots for about $1300. If I like the looks of it I may buy and settle up there it is on the line of the R Road to Perubina? and is a point to which the charter confines the road and is within 1 1/4 of the crossing of the Mississippi near 1 1/4 miles the junction of the Superior and Perubina? Road. If I should go then I will let you know sometime. Unless I see something that is quite inviting before fall I think that I shall go to farming. I am satisfied that I can make a living at that business and make myself a home although it may be an humble
Completed

one, and I feel as though I wanted a place to call home, where I can have Percie with me. It is no use I cannot talk fast enough, cannot farm and flatten the egotism of people sufficiently to keep up in the hurry and scramble of this age. I turn from it with loathing and disgust. I had rather bring Percie up a stranger to every advantage of civilized society than that he should become and adept in the arts and practices which lead to place and preferment at this day. Every body here seems to be possessed with a spirit of adventure and speculation. little or no thought is paid to those things which go to make up the comforts and happiness of home life and fireside pleasures. I hope, the grace of God helping me, to give
Completed

my little influence for the right. Gary for me that I may be enabled to resist the evil and stand for the truth.
About Percie, I feel very glad that I did not bring him out with me. I know that he much better off with you and is probably happier than he would be here. I do not know that I can give you any advice about him, do with him all things as you think best. If I should say anything it would be, require strict obedience to your every request, but I know there is no need of my saying this. May our Heavenly Father strengthen you and guide by his wisdom in all your labor of love
Tell Percie Father sends him a kiss.
Affectionately,
S.W. Furber
Completed

Tuesday morning, May 26th/57
It is till raining. I have made a fire in the office, swept out and been to the Post Office. got "many" letters. The spring here is very backward and cold. But no more so than below, the trees are putting on a layer of green. This Western Country is not so level as I expected to see it. The prairie grass is shorter than I supposed and the prairie fires far less magnificent, in all other respects it fully comes up to my anticipation, the land is very fertile and produces abundantly all crops but hayer which this soil does not seem well adapted. Hay is worth here now $50 per ton, a great deal of hay was burnt on the meadows last fall and the winter has been one of unusual
Completed

severity. a great many cattle have died from exposure and want of feed. This difficulty of growing hy is one of the disadvantages of this country. This is certainly a good place for a farmer and will be for a long time to come. The Emigration to this Territory. The Lumbering. The Mining and the Rail Roading must for many years make a home market
two years ago Theodore, after reserving what he wanted to supply his family, sold produce to the amount of $4000, from the product of less than 100 acres. Theodore came here 11 years ago last fall with about $700, he has been sick a good deal, had one years crop destroyed by fire and his house burned, and is now I should judge worth from $12,000 to $15,000, but to get this he he has worn himself out, I greatly
Completed

fear that he will be with us but a short time. he's troubled much with bronchitis and dispepsy, nd is very much debilitated. has had two attacks of diarrhea since I have been here, which at this season of the year seem to me to indicate much weakness,
Everything here seems to bear the impress of haste, there is nothing that seems to be finished. Three percent is the spirit of the age, nobody can or will use money for any other purpose when they can get from 3 to 5 percent per month for it, I settled some business for Theodore since I came here, he loaned $500 March 1st 1856, January 7th, 1857 he received on the note $100, and May 13th 1857 I collected the balance of $677.50 and still the man who hired it made money. He bought at Prescott
Completed

in the fall of 1855, 14 1/3 acres of land for $900, when he paid the note he sold 11 acres of this land for $3500. These things account for the haste there is here, and the want of attention to the little things that go to make up life. I have not become much acquainted here yet, have been introduced to but two Ladies in St. Paul and one of those last evening, a Mrs. Goodwin, who is from Racine, and was acquainted with Anna there, I think I can tell now I like the place after becoming more acquainted,. If the ladies are as much possessed of the age of 3 percent as the men are, I don't believe I shall like them.
Much love with best wishes and a promise to write again.
Samuel
S.W. Furber
St. Paul, May 27th
